														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2416053">
									

<p>So the Foundation secretly transferred a handful of test aircraft (only seven were ever built) from the Navy to the Air Force and had them armed and made combat ready in order for the UIU to use them to quickly respond to the Tango Tango incident? Wouldn't just letting the Air Force use the F-111A (or - E), which the USAF already had ready to go at the time? Is there some numerological reason for the -B that I am missing here? Or is it possible that the author doesn't know as much about 1970s combat aircraft as we do? Occam's Razor says the latter is more likely.</p>
<p>ETA: I'm saying that this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>UIU Central ordered US Air Force F-111B jets to be scrambled and eliminate the ships.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Ought to be &quot;F-111A jets&quot; (or &quot;F-111E jets&quot; or maybe even -Ds not sure if there were operational squadrons yet). Rather than any need for a contrived reason for the Air Force to be flying non-production Naval prototypes on a fast reaction combat sortie.</p>

							</div>

								
